Hey @SmarterEveryDay, quick question: Which is better, a round tip bullet or a cone under water? Would the increased pressure mean that a rounder tip would fly straighter due to suffering less internal vibrations (like a submarine trying to run quieter), or would a long tip be better all around since a bullet is solid instead of hollow like a submarine? I noticed that in the slowmo guy's video the hollow point went straighter through the water, but they didn't mention how far either of their shots flew like you did, and they never mentioned the caliber of bullet. I also noticed that your AK bullet tumbled much more than theirs did, probably due to its more conical shape and internal vibrations, as well as the length of the round with more mass at the tail end. Once sideways, I imagine it lost a lot of accuracy, and likely a lot of momentum. Given it has higher mass and more powder, it might have still flown just as far or even farther, but I still wonder which of the three flew the farthest and the straightest.

I wonder all of these things because I'm making a Sci-fi that takes place on a planet with higher air pressure, and warfare is involved. I'm curious which bullet would be more effective on an alien world with a soupy atmosphere. That being said, water is still significantly more dense and resistant than the atmosphere of my alien world, so maybe it wouldn't ultimately matter too much. So instead, this is probably more just a curiosity.

Awesome video!  I don't believe the water is cavitating in the barrel, though.  Due to the hydraulic pressure induced by the projectile, the fluid is still in laminar flow much like the inside of an aerosol can.  Once the fluid reaches the end of the barrel (the nozzle), the water column trips into turbulent flow and either vaporizes and/or goes aerosol (a.k.a. cavitates)--Evident by the cloud starting in the flash suppressor and mushroom head coming out of the barrel first.  The Rayleigh-Plesset principle actually starts at the interface of those two pressure condition (hydraulic-to-ambient).  I wish there was an infra-red version of this video, because I would love to see the heat dissipation signature once the propellant gas and residue leave the barrel. I don't think Destin can invoke Bernoulli's principle as simply as he did in this video. It's not correct to say "faster moving fluids exert less pressure". The fluid flows you are comparing first have to start out at the same total pressure. A more precise statement of Bernoulli's equation is "the total pressure of a fluid (static pressure plus dynamic pressure) is constant along a streamline". These initial conditions for Bernoulli's equation are not satisfied in the case described here. An example of this is blowing a jet of air out of your mouth. This jet of air does not intrinsically have a lower static pressure than the surrounding (still) air because as you blew it out of your mouth you increased its total pressure. The two parcels of air you are trying to compare did not start at the same total pressure.

Very interesting video and thorough analysis of what is happening during the phases of discharge of the round, but I have a thought or two about the "flash," or "sonoluminescence" (sp?) as you describe it, attributing the flash to sunlight reflection.
While that is certainly a possibility, I would posit this concept to run by you for your consideration.
I've seen additional video footage made by others where they were NOT outside in direct sunlight, so the optical appearance of the flash cannot be attributed to sunlight reflection.
This is where my idea factors in.
Feel free to give your thoughts as well.
MY suggestion is that unburned gunpowder (the dark cloud) that exists the bore of the gun, while inside the "bubble" is compressed as the bubble collapses creating an ersatz chamber outside of the gun itself, actually.
As the unburned powder is compressed and consisting of sufficient heat and oxygen molecules to support combustion, the UNBURNED powder is then ignited causing the second flash.
Think about it for a moment.
We always (?) see a large fireball upon detonation of the cartridge powder that occurs OUTSIDE the bore. That all is unburned powder still burning outside of the barrel which causes the flash.
So those powder particles, still needing to burn off, are given the means to do so inside the expanding then contracting bubble, still hot enough to support ignition, then doing so when the conditions inside the bubble/chamber are just right.
And the rebounding bubble as you point out bounces, if you will, through several cycles until the atmospheric conditions equalize.
So there you have it. My thoughts on the cause and effects of the underwater "flash" that happens as the bubble collapses.

I don't think the gas from the piston cycles the weapon - it is just enough to unlock the bolt. The pressure inside the barrel is what does the main job. The same pressure that pushes the bullet forwards is what pushes now the empty shell from the cartridge and the bolt backwards. If the bolt is not locked the bolt would go back way to soon and a lot of the gasses and the energy will simply be lost. The reason we have those gas operated rifles is so we give maximum inertia to the bullet possible but not wait to much because if the bolt is unlocked too late then the gases will escape the barrel after the bullet has come out and there won't be any pressure left to cycle the bolt. That's why the position of the small hole on the barrel that takes small part of the gas pressure to unlock the bolt is so important - too close to the end of the barrel - you risk experiencing a jam, too close to the entrance - the bolt will unlock and the pressure will escape way too soon before the bullet gets is maximum speed.

Also, remember that pressure is very much directional.  It is simply an average force over an area... and the force in a liquid or gas can be directed so that more of the average motion of the particles are in a certain direction and hence the average force exerted is also higher in that direction.  In static equilibrium, pressure is essentially equal in all directions over a small surface area at the same depth.  But while flowing the pressure is generally only lower at the boundaries orthogonal to the flow.  The pressure is actually higher along and in the direction of the flow than against the boundaries of the flow (i.e. tube walls).  If the pressure were also lower in the direction of the flow, it would be lower than the water outside the barrel and so it would not escape the barrel, rather it would be pushed back further inside the barrel by the higher-pressure water outside!  But that's not what happens.  I mention this because like so many other subtle--but often repeated--incomplete ideas in science can spread misconception later on.

At the point of implosion when there is a flash of light (and Destin considers sonar luminescence), notice that the image of the muzzle (and the rest of the frame for that matter) jostles back and forth.  I would guess that about the same time it takes for the first bubble implosion is when the most energetic wave reaches the mirror box.  It would be no coincidence that the bubble oscillation would then be in phase with the waves reaching the mirror.  So Destin is likely correct that it is not sonar luminescence and likely a "reflection of the sunlight", but more specifically the change in apparent brightness is due to variation in angle of combined refraction/reflection through the mirror box.  If the camera were moved or the box manually vibrated, one might also see a change in the apparent brightness of the overall image.  The effect is just more pronounced when it occurs in sync with the bubbles.

This video is awesome! Great work. :D I skimmed through the thread and didn't see it mentioned, so I thought I would drop a comment. A lot of people look at bernoulli and lose sight of what it's saying - it really only applies to static systems in a gravity field. You have either pressure head or potential energy, and if you stab a hole in the tank at the bottom he pressure is converted to kinetic energy. I'm not sure if you did that in your explanation at the end but I though I would put up how I'm thinking about what's happening and you can decide for yourself.

The instant the shot is fired the front of the bullet will transfer the pressure from behind the bullet and the water bullet system will be pushed out of the barrel as a slug. The pressure in the water in this instant has to increase because it is accelerating and we are putting energy into the system. As the liquid water hits the end of the barrel it will act to accelerate the body of water around it in a turbulent spray like mess that we see in the video. The momentum imparted here is enough to overcome the pressure exerted by the atmosphere and a bubble starts to form of near vacuum water vapor behind it. The bullet is ejected and travels through the liquid water immediately in front of it driven by the gasses from combustion behind it. it travels through the near vacuum and the gasses from combustion fill the bubble. The bullet hits the far site of the vacuum and it's momentum is transferred in an organized fashion from the leading edge of the bullet. As the bullet slows the angle that the momentum extends away from the bullet changes from near perpendicular when the speed of the bullet was near the speed of sound in water to near straight ahead of it as it's speed is much slower than that of the speed of sound in water. The corkscrew pattern is a consequence of the bullet having spin and not imparting it's momentum to the water uniformly. As the pressure from the atmosphere slows and reverses the momentum imparted to the water from the bullet, the bubbles stop expanding and start collapsing. There is very little area to close from the entry hole of the bullet into the second bubble it made, and there are very little gasses in this bubble beyond water vapor. The first bubble collapses and compresses the combustion gasses which forms a spring the incoming boundary of water bounces off of. The second bubble collapses to almost nothing because there are no gasses in there, and as you were saying is a sono-luminescence candidate - although I don't think it will because the spin of the bullet will make the boundary helical and have uneven pressures at the boundary which will promote water vapor going back to water liquid.

Love your channel. Wanted to put this out there as bernoulli was all the rage for a while and it was fashionable to talk in those terms when it was in vogue but it gets applied to a lot of areas where it's a really ineffective way of thinking through the problem (Airplane wings.. looking at you...). I thought you might be interested in walking through a process around conserving momentum. Momentum is always conserved. If energy is also conserved than Bernoulli's equation can be used to yield equivalent results in sometimes more convent metrics. Note, Navier stokes - the equations fluid mechanics is based on - is all based on conservation on momentum.

Some of my own observations and theories. That Barrell really flexes underwater, I think the pressure to the piston, and the piston mechanism contribute to this. Also, I think the column of water in front of the projectile is actually moving the piston, if not completely it is at least starting the movement early. If you take the cyclic operation of the AK into consideration, the piston, rod, bolt all only move back a small bit under power from the piston, until the piston passes the holes you talked about letting the gas bubbles out. That small bit unlocks the bolt. Once unlocked, the bolt itself is pushed back by blowback of the round (like a standard automatic pistol). In this case, that blowback is much more than normal because of the increased chamber pressure due to the water in the barrel as you already discussed.

Again, this is all just my own theories. I haven't read thru ALL of the comments, so if someone else already brought these up then criticism/credit naturally belongs where due.

Collapsing bubbles in pure darkness have been known to create a small burst of light.

"Spectral measurements have given bubble temperatures in the range from 2300 K to 5100 K, the exact temperatures depending on experimental conditions including the composition of the liquid and gas.[2] Detection of very high bubble temperatures by spectral methods is limited due to the opacity of liquids to short wavelength light characteristic of very high temperatures."

Great video, thanks, although I don't think your explanation for the first cloud out of the barrel - based on Bernoulli - is correct. The fact that the cloud grows radially from the axis of the barrel proves that the pressure in the cloud is greater than the local water pressure. It's not a region of low pressure. Just because there's a high velocity flow of fluid does not mean that you can apply Bernoulli and conclude that the pressure is less in that flow. For instance, if you squirt water from a hose into your pool or against your garage, the collision will produce increased (stagnation) pressure in the region of the collision. A submerged jet, however, will cause regions of reduced pressure; i.e., in regions outside the jet proper, where fluid is entrained ("pulled along") by the main jet.

An alternate explanation is that the cloud is a mixture of water and combustion products (gas) from the gunpowder. The mixture is caused by the extreme turbulence caused by the gunpowder explosion. This cloud can flow out of the barrel faster than the bullet because some gas always leaks between the projectile and the sides of the barrel, moving faster than the bullet. (You can see this on other YouTube videos.) This explanation is consistent with the fact that the rebound explosion that you noted also looks like a cloud, and again, I think it's a mixture of gas and water, forcibly mixed by the high pressure collision caused by the previous collapse of the bubble. (Do you have an alternative explanation why the rebound looks so much more frothy than the first bubble?)

Finally, in order to form a bow shock in front of a moving projectile in a fluid, the projectile must be traveling greater than the velocity of sound in that fluid. I don't know what the muzzle velocity of an AK47 is, but I doubt very much it's any where near the speed of sound in water (about 5 x the velocity in air), and even more so, especially after it has been slowed down tremendously by the water.

But I don't mean to take anything from this very interesting and well made video, and it was a welcomed surprise to see someone talking real Physics on a YouTube channel. I look forward to more videos. Thanks again.

The AK47 is a German Designed weapon based on the Sturmgewehr 44 - STG44.
Today the Russians openly admit that in October 1945, Hugo Schmeisser (the father of the STG44) and 15 of his engineeringteam were deported from their homes in the "Weapon City of Shul" in East Germany, to the Soviet were they were put to work in what today is known as the official Kalashnikov factory: IZHMASH. While working in the factory their closest man on the floor was Mikhail Kalashnikov. After 7 years of work Hugo and his team were released. Hugo died in his home in 1953.

A Russian Weapon speciallist and scientist named Anton Kalmikov are openly critical and says: "It is completley absurd to believe that a Russian engineer could have developed the AK47. Because such a design requires a highly advanced engineering expretise that the Soviet simply did not posess during that time".

Hugo Schmeisser and his team will not recieve any recognition for the development of the AK47. But that isn't strange at all. No nation would give an enemy POW creds for such an iconic invetion so Mikhail was given the honor. But fact still remains: The AK47 is essentially a German Developed weapon. And it comes as no purprise when come to think of it. It is known to never fail, which is typical of German Quality. Unlike Russian quality that is known to break down by itself. Like what Nicolas Cage says in the movie "Lord of War": "Since the end of the Cold War the Kalashnikov has become the Russian peoples greatest export...one thing was sure, no one was lining up to buy their cars". Which is still true to this day.

Very interesting video with complicated fluid physics.
feel the bow shock explanation may be misleading, typical speeds of AK47 bullets are about 700 m/s while speed of sound in water is 1500 m/s. Which implies we are still in the subsonic regime (M ~ 0.5). Two interesting things to note

1) We cannot claim the bullet is enclosed in the clearer second bubble and the shockwave is inside the bubble. This is possible because speed of sound in water vapor is sqrt(g RT) ~ 400 m/s. It is clearly seen from the video that the cavitation happens in the middle of the bubble in the streamwise direction.

2) It could be that the bullet is travelling at what aerodynamicists call critical mach number which means at some point on the bullet, the flow is sonic and a normal shock appears. If that is the case I would expect the bubble formed on the bullet to have a sharp interface.

So think the cavitation effect on the bullet is due to pressure reduction from higher fluid speeds on its surface. The initial bubble from the barrel is complicated because of cavitation of water from the inside the barrel and the turbulence generated by the bullet. Viscous and pressure drag slows down the bullet towards the end to creates a simpler bubble profile, which may not have to do with shockwaves at all.

OK gotta question your application of Bernoulli here. Bernoulli's principle assumes A) Steady flow -- not applicable. B) Comparison of two points within a streamline -- totally not applicable. I'd question whether you can even treat water as incompressible here.

Also, Newton's 2nd law directly contradicts your theory: if the bullet and contents of the barrel are accelerating from the barrel, by definition they must have a greater pressure than the surrounding water (equal cross-sections, presumably).

My alternatives: With this much energy imparted, the water leaving the barrel can't just mix with the surrounding water (read: NOT inviscid, another point against Bernoulli?). Instead, the water rapidly leaving the barrel could be treated as a projectile itself, causing cavitation behind it just like the bullet eventually does. Or your shear stress from the exiting jet causes cavitation, shear cavitation is well documented.

Just my two cents, please correct me if I'm missing something here..

After shooting an AK under water, I had the unfortunate problem of realizing that it somehow caused the chrome to peel away from the inside of the bore.  I don't know why this happened.  After sending the rifle in to get fixed, I tried again, with better results by keeping the muzzle pointed downwards to keep air in the barrel while under water.  Unfortunately after this I convinced myself I just had a bad first barrel, and allowed the water to fill the barrel before firing again, AGAIN causing the chrome to peel away from the underlying metal of the bore.  All I can figure is that the water is being pressed into micrscopic flaws in the chrome and pressurized to a point where it invades the space between the steel and the chrome causing it to flake off in great large chunks.  So yeah, check out your barrel with a bore scope- you almost certainly have fried your lining.  For what it's worth melonited barrels tend to show NO appreciable problems when fired under water.

That is really cool but I am not sure I agree with your conclusion. I think the explosive force/gases are actually leaking around the bullet and shoving the water out of the way. The initial cloud like blast out of the muzzle is the leaked gases that will travel much faster than the bullet. But than we see the dark powder residue following the bullet and the bullet traversing the hollow vacuum bubble to burst through and create its own vacuum bubble.
I think these funny looking bubbles are almost pure vacuum with the first cloud like bubble having some minute gasses that rapidly cool. The bullet will leave a pure vacuum at those temps. There should be no steam creation at those temps even from pure vacuum. 
The pulsation phenomenon is pretty cool. Water ram pumps are built on this principle and water piping installed improperly in a house can rattle from this same principle that has to do with mass and momentum. Momentum created from such a large vacuum collapsing is going to create a rediculous amount of force on the water. It acts like its bouncing on itself but the force is so great it creates a massive High pressure in a very teeny tiny area. Whether it actually creates a tiny steam explosion or just bounces back would make for some interesting tests. 
One extra test I would have liked to have seen would have been filling the barrel in front of the bullet with a dark blue or red dye. Hold it in there with a bit of tissue and filming that blast so as to better see where and how far that water goes. 
Cool experiments! Cant wait to see some more.

(wife's account) I notice the bullet yaw just past the the cavitation pocket. In some test I have seen, a bullet fired outside of water into the water usually on covers a distance of 3 feet. This cavitation effect seems to be giving the bullet an extra foot or so, I think because of the much less resistance imparted on the bullet.
Also, when shooting a 50 BMG the air inside the bbl forward of the bullet is compressed by the bullet. The compressed air comes out of the muzzle brake 'before' the bullet has passed the muzzle, causing movement of the gun. Any shooter not following the six steps to firing the shot, will find their shots are not nearly as accurate as that of a 7.62 NATO or other smaller bore rifles. More data on this in 'Complete .50-Caliber Sniper Course : Hard-Target Interdiction'. The AMU had to rethink the training of Hard Target training because of this previously unknown effect.   Thanks for a great video!

This is what I think is going on with those lighting bursts. When the shock barrier hits the little particles right in front of the gun (which I guess are some metal splinters peeled off the bullet) the water starts to scatter around this particles becoming gas. Thus, the surrounding gas makes an irregular thin film of vapor that scatters the light the same way a diffuse surface does, and since the average count of photons bounced off of a specular surface at a given geometry (like cilinders which is the most likely form for the splinters) are less than the mean light reflected by an irregular surface. So, they look brigther.

Its higher than the pressures when the rifle is shot in the air. I'm not sure what the tolerances are for the barrel and gas block, but I have seen them bulge in other videos. You will definitely know when you try to shoot a target and the bullet falls out of the end of the barrel, or worse yet the barrel explodes.  The same goes for pistols and revolvers. If you have a gun that you would like to be able to shoot, DO NOT fire it under water.

Couple things--one, it's interesting how the bullet immediately starts to tumble on exit--the rifling, so effective in air, is virtually worthless underwater, then there's the Rayleigh-Plesset effect.  Cool.  As for the sono-luminescence...just try doing it in the dark.  Problem solved.

The "Bubble bounce" is actually much simpler than the gas pushing the bubble out faster than the water pressure can keep up, it's the bullet's velociity itself and the bow shock pushing the water apart faster than water's sound barrier, and creating a vacuum pocket around the path of the bullet. That's why the shrinking of the "bubble" happens so rapidly, and the bounce is actually an implosion/explosion. The cavitation's collapse causing sonoluminescence (and/or triboluminscence from the friction of the water as it slams into itself ) would not be unheard of, as bubbles that are extremely small created from ultrasonic pulses can also cause sonoluminescence.

When I first saw this, I was thrilled at the cavitation effects! I think there is much more to the whole cavitation effect than we really understand... with sonoluminescence only a small part of the whole effects.

The collapse of the "cavity" is incredibly powerful... and results in marine propeller pitting, and failures. It actually blasts off small bits & pieces of the prop metal by creating a highly supersonic water jet (like in a water cutting machine) as the cavity collapses, and the water rushes back in towards the prop.

The sonoluminescent bubbles from cavitation have been analyzed, and indicate temperatures around 20000 K (35,500 degrees F) - though some say it's much higher... as high as 1 MILLION DEGREES Kelvin!!

It'd be awesome to see a night-time high speed video of this same experiment!!

Id' have to say though, I'm somewhat surprised the barrel withstands that kind of force... pushing that much water out of the way - that fast... creates pressures we can't fathom.

A modified version of this experiment would be very interesting... a piece of cellophane tape over the end of the barrel, submersing only the front half of the barrel. The bullet speed would then be full, not damped by the water in the barrel.  I'm sure you'd need a good target material to shoot at though, as the bullet would clearly travel MUCH farther.

Destin, I have a comment/question about the pressure.  Since the pressure of the system (the bubble) is super-high at initiation, and causes the system to initially expand, the pressure in the system should already be past the pressure equilibrium point between itself and the surroundings (the water), right?  Otherwise, you wouldn't have initial expansion.  The system expands until equilibrium is reached, and then is compressed by the surroundings, when the surroundings contain greater pressure than the system.  Then the process continues as you described. After expansion has begun, there shouldn't be a later point in the expansion of the system where equilibrium is passed, because it is already past equilibrium with the initial expansion.  I basing this off of the kinetics I learned in physical chemistry, so I think that's right, but I'd be glad to know if I'm mistaken.

Believe it! That "bubble" is actually known as supercavitation. That's not air you're seeing, that's actually water vapor. Water vapor is typically invisible (steam is condensed water vapor, technically back to a liquid) and that vapor bubble is actually under negative pressure. When that vapor re-condenses, it pulls the surrounding water in faster than the speed of sound, creating a sonic boom of sorts. Check out the "pistol shrimp" which uses the same process to stun it's prey.

Did you also notice the very brief flash of light right as the cavity collapses on itself? If I remember correctly, when it collapses, it creates an extremely high temperature that burns very bright for a split second. I saw a video some time ago showing that principle using nothing more than a "syringe" piston and a small piece of cotton and they were able to light the cotton with nothing more than the extremely high air pressure.

7.62x39 mags have a very steep curvature. .223 only requires a slight curve to the mags while .308 can be fired out of straight-walled mags. 5.45x39 mags are somewhere in the middle of .223 and 7.62x39, but this was clearly the latter of those three.

The gas tube is just a guide for the gas piston and keeps the shooter's hand from being sprayed with combustion gases. There's a vent hole in gas block itself and that is where pressure stops acting on the piston face anyway, and the gap between the block and tube isn't exactly airtight. It's working as intended, you can just actually see all that venting underwater.

Why would there be cavitation in front of the barrel? The pressure definitely doesn't decrease. In order for the water to accelerate to a high velocity, there must be a force acting upon it, which comes from the bullet accerlating (force ~ 900N over length of barrel). Hydrostatic pressure is proportional to force, so the pressure must increase. In addition, Bernoulli's principle assumes laminar flow, which isn't the case, as inertial forces greatly outweigh viscous forces in the barrel.

The white bubble is induced along the inner wall of barrel or by muzzle device and then mixed with black smoke/exploded gas. After getting through the first bubble/initial cavitation, the bullet generates the second cavitation which is very clear, transparent, beautiful sheet cavitation with single bubble.

Hello, I just want to point out that the cavitation does not happen inside the barrel.
It does so at the exit of the barrel.
To break it down by phase: 
1) water inside the barrel will be pushed faster then it can exit creating a high pressure wave & increasing it's temperature.
2) once exiting the barrel, you have a condition of lower pressure, hence the exiting water column will expend to equilibrium pressure (Which make it switch from liquid state to vapor state). Hence the bubble is created.

The water absolutely goes out of the gun at a high pressure, otherwise it'd be sucked in. What happens IMO is that the high-pressure jet creates a small shockwave soon after it leaves the gun (see the cone/cylinder change in shape) and quickly drops its pressure when the bullet goes out of the gun as well, whilst the shockwave still has its momentum to grow. And *then* the low pressure creates the vapor.

Gravity does play a role, but the force (pressure) of the water is a function of depth. Where gravity comes into play is that it is pulling down on the column of water above the point of measurement. The pressure ends up being a function of the accumulated 'weight' of water above the point of measurement combined with the surface area of the object under pressure. This is why pressure is given per unit of area, eg. pounds per square inch (PSI).

Please do both of us the favor of reading and understanding cavitation. The bullet violently tries rushing through the incompressible liquid, moving faster than the liquid can close the gap behind it. You cant really end up with vacuum there so the water around the cavity (hence the name cavitation) simply 'boils' away because of the tremendous pressure difference. So the bubble is basically filled with evaporated water ->gaseous h2o.
You can clearly see gunpowder gases get mixed with that.

At 7:10, what you're seeing is not just a reflection from the sunlight above. It's much cooler. You are seeing sound waves. If you look closely, you can see that the brightness pattern propagates away from the big imploding bubble through the bubble cloud. What you are seeing is the decrease in radius of the bubbles in the bubble cloud. In the bubble cloud, the sound speed is 30 m/s, while it is 1500 m/s outside. As a result, the bubble cloud becomes a wave guide.

Unfortunately, I don't think the part around 7:40 about the cavitation within the barrel is correct.  Bernoulli's equation (in it's given form) is a heavily simplified version of the Euler equations; these simplifications place many constrains on when it can be used.  Two of them are steady flow and an inviscid fluid.  Neither of these are even close to true, so we really can't apply Bernoulli's equation to this and say that because the water in the barrel is moving fast, the pressure is low.

Great vid!

The multiple collapses are due to:

1 - (Un)compressibility of liquids. The weight of all the water in the pool is pushing back in. Trying in a completely sealed tank would reduce this effect.
Wiki: Liquids#Mechanical_properties

2 - Cavitation. Wiki: Cavitation

3 - Thermodynamics - Volume of the gas decreases as it cools from +-7500C to temp. of the water.
Wiki: Volume_Thermodynamics/Gas_volume

All this adds up to show one of the few situations where liquids seem "elastic". :)
